Title: The Surrender Experiment: My Journey into Life's Perfection
Author: Michael A. Singer
My Review:
I'm blown away by the twists and turns in his life. I feel like I need to do my own deep dive to see how true all the events in this book are.

I still have some questions left about the difference between surrendering to life vs being a pushover vs not having agency. It's difficult to figure out what's "the flow" and the extent you should assert your own flow.

This book has left me with enough of an impression to start meditating (just 5 minutes each day to start) and quiet the voice in my head. The concept is the most relatable thing in this book I've heard of and makes me feel incredibly seen. I wish I had read this book 10 years ago and learned to find stillness sooner, but better now than never!

I love memoirs like this which show a drastically way of living a rich, fulfilling life.

Title: Steve Jobs
Author: Walter Isaacson
My Review:
This is my second Walter Isaacson biography and I really admire the lengths he goes to to paint such a detailed picture of someone's life! Maybe a bit too lengthy but consuming this as an audiobook means I can half concentrate and I still get the broad strokes of things.

Some things I took away:
- the importance of having a vision!! It's so powerful to be able to imagine what the world could be like beyond the limits of what is currently possible then work towards it.
- relentless pursuit of simplicity ! Making products that are so intuitive you don't need instructions or complicated steps. Things just happen.
- building your product based on other products limits what you're able to do - but going around this also means being willing to invest in building every part of your product from scratch. If you have a strong sense of your core product, you'll make a better informed decision on whats worth it (related to having a vision!)
- seamless integration!! In a world where it pays to specialise, it's becoming more valuable to specialise in workflows from end to end as opposed to making specific tasks generalisable. (Think: being the best burger restaurant as opposed to the best patty supplier)
- there is power in confidence, especially to others. Lots of people are often waiting for "permission" to do things and when you give it to them, they can move mountains.
- As with many of these insane people, I'd hate it if readers were to takeaway that being an asshole is the key to success -- you can be kind while being tough, honest without being malicious and confident without being cocky.

Title: Battle Hymn of the Tiger Mother
Author: Amy  Chua
My Review:
I think it's pretty insane how confident she can feel about what's right for her daughters and what would actually help them "succeed" in life. Entertaining and eye-opening!

Some points that stuck out to me:
- letting your kids choose whatever they want isn't parenting. In many ways they often don't know enough to choose themselves (but I think there's also a degree to which you should allow your child to express their preferences)
- getting your child to persevere instead of giving up helps build character (but I do think she went way overboard). There's a default state for giving up or doing what's easiest and sometimes it takes someone who knows better to show the child that the harder path will be better in the long run.
- Really would like to know if there's some research done about why second children tend to be more rebellious than the eldest child

Title: What We Owe Each Other: A New Social Contract for a Better Society
Author: Minouche Shafik
My Review:
I appreciated the format of the historical examples tied to an outline of a potential policy, and going through policies for each stage of people's lives and how they tie in with each other.

Quick notes of what I remember the book advocating for:
- investment in education (particularly at the early ages to get the highest returns)
- finding ways to keep people productive for longer (e.g. lifelong learning, revising pension schemes based on life expectancy)
- reducing burdens on families especially women to care for the elderly
- getting multinational countries to pay their share of taxes so states get the appropriate revenue for policies
- everyone deserves access to basic healthcare, opportunities to advance and some form of pension
- revising the social contract in a way that spreads the burdens evenly among all members of society.

Randomly today I noticed that my GP uses a similar set of questions as the cultural questions from the book when I was booking an appointment online! Title: What My Bones Know: A Memoir of Healing from Complex Trauma
Author: Stephanie Foo
My Review:
I learned so much about healing and self-love from this book and would 100% recommend this to anyone going through their own journey. I particularly enjoyed the way she summarised research and reframed it to how applicable it is to her life or cautions with the specific assumptions the research was made under. I gobbled up the audiobook and felt my perspective change.

Here's what I took away:
1. Just because you 'tried therapy' and it didn't work, doesn't mean that therapy doesn't work for you. Sometimes it just means that the therapist or the method didn't address your needs.
2. You need to process how you feel and accept those feelings as they come along. You can't just shut feelings out.
3. It's okay to feel sad especially right after particularly amazing days. It's a natural response that you want more amazing days but you shouldn't beat yourself up for feeling that way. Accept it and let go.
4. Curiosity! A way to practice active listening. Understand why you reacted in certain ways -- ask questions from a place of kindness. And when you have the emotional availability, do this for your loved ones too. Everyone has insecurities, doubts - help them work through it, ask them questions to understand how they feel.
5. Taking care of your mental health is taking care of your physical health. They are intertwined!
6. One way to better understand your emotions is to make sure you're taking care of yourself (eat well, drink water, sleep enough, exercise). Then, you can begin to discern where your feelings are coming from.

I'd love to re-read this book after I've digested it. I am learning to look after myself and I think this will help.

also thinking on it Jacks is an interesting character because he's feels like the antagonist (or at least the only known one) but also not really?? He definitely causes a lot of the tension that drives the plot and Evangeline wanting so much to do the 'right thing' which she decided

Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review:
Honestly one of the best books I've EVER read! The writing style is riveting from start to end, I've never seen someone make such creative use of pronouns.

I was thoroughly confused throughout the book and still am. I feel like I'm being handed tiny clues along the way but these clues are infinitesimally small compared to what's _really_ going on. It's the kind of suspense that makes you want to reread the book. It's the kind of character building that makes you want to restart your relationship with the character over and over again because each is just so complex.

I loved reading this book so much and i can't wait to finish the series so i can read it all over again. HIGHLY recommend!!

Title: To Sleep in a Sea of Stars
Author: Christopher Paolini
My Review:
More like a 3.5 but I couldn't bring myself to rank it among the actual 4 star books here :(
- I cannot take the names given to the antagonists of the book seriously. Jellies? Nightmares? It's just uninspiring and flat
- Amazing detail on space travel in the appendix, though I wish these sci-fi concepts were weaved better in the actual novel. Honestly, the appendix was one of the most engaging parts of the book.
- The book also just felt way longer than it should be. I kept thinking it would end at multiple points but there were a few different plot twists that just kept the story going.
- I feel fairly disconnected from Kira. I don't hate her, I don't love her, I don't resonate with her. I'm just ambivalent which is unfortunate given that we follow her throughout the story.

For sci-fi concepts, I'd actually recommend the Appendix HAHA, but I'm not sure I would recommend the story in itself.

Title: Radio Silence
Author: Alice Oseman
My Review:
I like the idea that university doesn't have to be the end all be all... But despite the sense of realism the book tries to convey about the actual merits of a formal education, I'm left at the end of the book feeling a bit unsatisfied. I've felt for the most part like I could see myself in her, and I could reasonably be her. Then towards the end i just don't. There is a note of happily ever after, I suppose I'm just hung up on the ever after.

I guess what I'm trying to say is, the characters had a lot of potential to be developed further!


But that isn't to say you shouldn't read the book. I loved the pacing of the story, it reads really well. I love the representation of platonic friendships in a YA novel. With the mainstream of relationships in YA it almost seems as though romantic love is the default form for the main characters to take. Love has always been central to the equation. But it's beautiful to imagine a universe where it doesn't have to be. Where you could love fiercely without the sexual attraction, where you could feel warmed by a relationship without the romance.

Title: The Places I've Cried in Public
Author: Holly Bourne
My Review:
I am blown away. At first I thought I was a dumb book about teenage love but as I kept reading, it was so much more profound than. It's a process, its all the unspoken feelings we have about falling into a strange relationship. And it's funny that you believe you'll never be _that_ girl, how you're immune bad relationships to this because you know. But sometimes you can't see it. And this book is a beautiful, heart-wrenching reminder of that.

Thank you Holly Bourne. For putting to words feelings I could not articulate, for showing me what I could not see myself.

Title: The Revenge of Seven (Lorien Legacies, #5)
Author: Pittacus Lore
My Review:
Reading through I was wondering why I couldn't really connect with any of the characters well. I still find John annoying even though this is already the fifth book. Nine's charm that I found interesting in the second and third book now make him look like a douche. I won't go onto a hate rampage, but I suppose the underlying reason is that I feel like the characters haven't been developed well enough. There is not enough time invested to their thought process and emotions as each individual character. After all, we mostly only get a glimpse of John or Six, but even with the extra exposure to how they think I still can't quite grasp them as real people. The story itself is interesting and I enjoy the concept of it. However, at one point of the book when Setrakus Ra arrives in New York at the last few chapters and becomes so overtly distraught that this part of his plan has been foiled I felt underwhelmed by the situation. It felt so out of character and forced (probably because the antagonist of the series feels kinda one dimensional to begin with).

All in all, not the greatest series, but I will finish it because I bought the box set HAHA

Title: All the Bright Places
Author: Jennifer Niven
My Review:
He was a shining character for the majority of the book. He was everything at once at one go, but I guess thats what happens when stars burn too brightly: they explode and leave a yawning black hole in their wake. Congratulations Finch you've made your Great Manifesto, but it would've been greater if you stayed with Violet.

That's the thing about fighting your inner demons, you forget that in the civil war against yourself, you will always lose. To me mental instability isn't about fighting the Battle and winning to be whole again. It's forming an alliance with the enemy and learning to co-exist in that space within your head because like it or not your demons are viscerally a part of you. Rip them out and you'll destroy a part of yourself too.

The challenge being brave enough to face the truth of your Self.

Title: The Rest of Us Just Live Here
Author: Patrick Ness
My Review:
There's something about the way that Patrick Ness writes books that makes you feel something deep within yourself. In this case it's an unbearable sadness at the reality of it all from what the characters are going through. The emotions and ideas he conveys are powerful and relatable. I'm crying from how this book has touched something in my heart.

The thing about Patrick Ness is that from reading the Monsters of Men trilogy and A Monster Calls is that his stories take on their own lives. It's never about just writing a book to live out the fantasy, it's about writing about a life to live out its meaning. It's really difficult to explain how I feel about his stories but they always leave me in a book hangover state for a while.

This book contrary to what many reviews seem to be saying isn't boring because it's about the non-supernatural kids. It's amazing because it's about how supernatural they can be in their own way.

Totally recommended for those who love war stories without the gore!

My Review:
The book had a good concept about how you enter dreams and things like that. But what I really liked about the book was the realism of the character. She was seriously between a rock and a hard place in the book and I like how they didn't overly romanticise the fact that she chose Cabel.

Title: Skinny
Author: Donna Cooner
My Review: You never really truly understand how it feels like to be fat, stupid or anything for that matter unless you've lived through it yourself. Even reading this book I would only be able to catch a glimpse of what it must be like to be 302 pounds. It brought me to tears at some parts of this story. I am sure many people have that voice in their head telling them what's wrong with them when in actual fact sometimes all we need is someone to open our eyes. To even imagine finding someone who loves you whether you're 302 pounds or 100 pounds is the most beautiful thing in the world. This book is really something else and I 100% recommend you to read it. You won't regret it.
